Difficult work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Mohammad Mursi went to another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play a bargain.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of all others, that the Constituent Assembly would come to approve the final text.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using the provisional text, which has been supplemented many times, which weakens the country’s constitutional stability and leads to legal agreements.
This new initiative only further reinforced the country’s fragmentation.
From the point of view of the opposition, the president remains in his "autocratic deliry", continuing to "broke his word" and "slapping the right".
His supporters, however, ensure that it is a means to tackle the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transitional process.
A referendum should be held in two weeks.
It is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of texting the Egyptians to clarify article by article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the whole country rejects protests.
As confirmed in an interview for the American weekly Time, Muhammad Mursi appears to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote for.
Particularly because this fast-paced vote puts the Egyptian people before the ultimatum: "Either you approve my text, or I will leave unlimited powers" which would otherwise end after the new constitution is approved.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday, 85 members of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most of the liberals were missing in the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the proclamation of the constitution, they knocked on the door with no opportunity to enforce their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their move.
In order to achieve tolerance, 11 people from the ranks of substitutes were quickly supplemented yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is no surprise that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
The commentators further stood over the fact that one of the few controversies turned around that day... the hour of prayer, when some members of the committee held the view that the hours in the meeting room were not properly arranged.
The text, which was voted last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, remains in line with the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term "principle" with the term "rule", which would allow for more stringent application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for the other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocritism" is opposed by liberals, who see only a speech problem in this.
According to them, the islamization of the constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts al-Azhar University with an advisory role, in particular on issues of checking compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "people called to express themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of theocracy.”
The concerns of liberals are even more frustrating that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current.
“At the moment, no specific religious consequences have emerged.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not scumbags, but university workers, many of whom have graduated from French schools,” said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, they agree that "there may be controversy regarding the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
There is, in particular, a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, ed.].
And in the future, there may be a question of the extent to which civil judges are competent to express themselves.”
The text approved yesterday is highly criticized, in addition to the religious sides, for the extended powers that it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant restriction on them against the former regime.
Another controversial place: the powers entrusted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the army, the verification of the defence budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, the trials of civilians in military courts will not be prohibited, as required by the human rights association.
These associations speak about their doubts in connection with the text they believe is directed against freedom.
The criminal act of slander is retained and the offense is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially then for the press.
In addition, no article is about the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to perform in a televised speech last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The president’s supporters will be demonstrating on Saturday.
