Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of this European space agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and over the next few years participated in a number of projects of the Agency.
However, Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts devoted themselves to flying into space before the Second World War; but they did not always meet with understanding.
For example, I recall the lecture by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which presented ideas from his pioneering work on 6 December 1933.
The ideas of a young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and after years sternerfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, sternfeld received the award of Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his Entrance into the Cosmonautics in France.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous propagator of the cosmonautics and his contribution was also appreciated by one of the craters on the reverse side of the moon being named by his name.
Already in 1925 a railroad was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to take off the dredge or to brake it.
Information about this color is only known from the time print.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to be occupied by rockets.
The research was provided by the Arms Technology Cell in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckieg.
From the preserved materials, it is apparent that the research has reached the stage of practical trials.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of the photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work of the Rakete - an air torpedo and a rocket bomb by the author Leliwy-Krzywoblock.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Advisory Committee-Scientific Committee) was responsible for all projects of military use of rocket technology.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the war ended.
After the war, another work dedicated to the astronauts appeared in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautice).
For the first time there is a mention of the company in the November issue of the 1954 issue of the magazine Problems, in which four more comprehensive articles are devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At the time, projects of artificial satellites had already begun and it was clear that space research was a field of perspective.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn became a regular member of the PTA.
And in the following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautic Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of a very successful meteorological rocket RM (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The 1800-metre missile was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 missile was launched in the Bled Desert.
The missile was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of development was already to be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 was to have access to up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the altitude wind.
However, in 1962, further developments were suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket developed from 1962 to 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and a starting weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 litres, a Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and a Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum accessibility for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 was developed by the Aircraft Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket weighed 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remkov.
